<br>
 What you do is download that stuff (The IME pack) and then install it. After you install it and reboot, you should see a little thing in the bottom right that says, &quot;EN&quot; which stands for English, obviously. Then, if you click to type in a program that supports Japanese characters (Word, this BBS, and quite a few other programs, I've found), go down to the EN thing, left-click it, then there should be an option that says &quot;JA: Japanese IME&quot;. <br>
<br>
 After that, a little menu will pop up that has an A, a kanji symbol, a preferences box, and a help box. Click on the A then select the top option, that should make you be able to type in hiragana. You have to type proper things, though, like: I, wa, ya, ru, etc, etc. <br>
<br>
 To get your browser to recognize Japanese fonts, all you have to do is download the Japanese language pack from WindowsUpdate, then go to your browser and select VIEW/ENCODING, then Japanese (Auto-Select). After that, it should recognize any Japanese character that's on there. I was too dumb to figure all that out, so Mai had to tell me. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :\ --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/ohwell.gif ALT=":\"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
 But, yeah. I dunno if I worded that well enough to understand, but hopefully it'll work.<br>
