<br>
The thing is, though, is that Japanese fonts aren't meant to type English, or any other language for that matter. It's meant for Japanese. <br>
<br>
 In Hiragana and Katakana, the only single consonant there is, is N. The rest of the alphabet is made up of combinations of vowels and consonants. <br>
<br>
 Here's some charts:<br>
 Hiragana: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://jin.jcic.or.jp/kidsweb/language/hiragana.html">jin.jcic.or.jp/kidsweb/la...agana.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
 Katakana: <!--EZCODE AUTOLINK START--><a href="http://jin.jcic.or.jp/kidsweb/language/katakana.html">jin.jcic.or.jp/kidsweb/la...akana.html</a><!--EZCODE AUTOLINK END--><br>
<br>
 Those will show you the correct combinations. <br>
<br>
 Just don't try to type in: &quot;My name is Chris&quot; in English, and expect it to come out in Japanese. If you do that, it'll look like: ÇlÇô Ç»Çﬂ Ç¢Çì ÇbÇàÇËÇìÅB<br>
<br>
 Now if you type: &quot;Watashi no namae wa Kurisu desu&quot; the IME will pick up the combination of vowels and consonants and it will look something like: ÇÌÇΩÇµÇÃÇ»Ç‹Ç¶ÇÌÇ≠ÇËÇ∑Ç≈Ç∑ÅB<br>
<br>
 Correct me if I said anything incorrect.<br>
<br>
